{"source_key":"sha256-e5687aa6fc4c11d845e8d63e8ca8f175","record_index":173,"record_hash":"sha256:ee9907a46bab1c3b9c24880295fc22649c3aa57d73b7cdbef05ed48496a3c6c1","timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:30:57.386Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Short version: this is not “agent memory.” It’s Git-native provenance: capture agent sessions, attach them to branches/PRs through `git-meta`, publish only selected metadata, then render a reviewer-safe PR trail.\\n\\n**Component View**\\n\\n| Component | What it’s for | How it stores/surfaces data | Key limits |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| `git-meta` | Generic metadata layer for Git objects/projects, intended as a better notes-like system for prompts, provenance, review, tests, etc. See [README.md]([REDACTED:path]) and [spec]([REDACTED:path]). | Local SQLite at `.git/git-meta.sqlite`; exchange via Git refs/trees, especially `refs/meta/*`. API is `Session -> Target -> MetaValue`; CLI has set/get/list/sync/materialize/push/pull. See [session.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [schema.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [cli.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | It’s infrastructure, not UX. Higher-level tools must decide what to capture, redact, publish, and display. Docs explicitly leave a lot of integration work out of scope. |\\n| `but-agentlog` | GitButler-specific capture and interpretation of coding-agent sessions. It turns Codex/Claude transcript JSONL plus GitButler workspace context into structured git metadata. See [Cargo.toml]([REDACTED:path]), [lib.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | Stores project-target keys like `gitbutler:agent-session:<id>` and `local:gitbutler:agent-session:<id>` through `git-meta`; indexes by branch/review/change/session. Write path is in [write.rs]([REDACTED:path]). CLI surface is `hook`, `show`, `skim`, `publish`, hidden `sync` in [cli.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | Target association is partly heuristic. Supports Codex/Claude transcript shapes. Redaction is strong but still best-effort, so publication boundary matters. |\\n| `agent-trail` | PR review surface: “what did the agent appear to do while producing this PR?” It is evidence UI, not authorship proof. See [README.md]([REDACTED:path]), [docs]([REDACTED:path]). | Rust/Axum service with embedded React UI. Fetches `refs/meta/main`, materializes via `git-meta`, calls `but_agentlog::projection::project_pr`, then serves a bounded contract. See [http.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [repo_cache.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [trail_projection.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [trail_contract.rs]([REDACTED:path]). | Public docs still say v1 is public-only/no forks, but code has private repo/share-link machinery. Production policy needs confirmation. |\\n\\n**How They Work Together**\\n\\n1. `but-agentlog hook` receives a transcript path and cwd, parses Codex/Claude JSONL, extracts turns/tools/results, suppresses system/developer records, redacts text, and captures GitButler branch/review/change context. Parsing lives in [transcript.rs]([REDACTED:path]); environment targeting in [environment.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n2. It writes session metadata into `git-meta`, usually local-only first. Publication status is controlled by existing schema/config: `gitbutler.agentlog-share-default` decides new-session default when no prior schema exists. See [write.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n3. `but-agentlog publish` moves selected local session/index data into published keys and syncs metadata. See [share.rs]([REDACTED:path]) and [cli.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n4. `git-meta` serializes SQLite rows into Git trees/commits and syncs refs. Important semantics: `local:` keys never serialize; filters can route/exclude keys; conflicts use explicit tombstones and mostly local-wins merge behavior. See [serialize-filters.md]([REDACTED:path]), [materialize.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [push.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n5. `agent-trail` resolves a GitHub PR, fetches metadata into a repo cache, materializes it, calls `but-agentlog` projection, then renders a reviewer-safe trail. Cache key includes PR facts, metadata OID, and projection version. See [snapshot.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n**Capabilities**\\n\\n- Branch/PR/change-associated agent session lookup, not just chronological chat history.\\n- Bounded skim/show views for local orientation. See [skim.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Public projection with opaque handles, redaction, truncation, no raw session IDs/source records/tool payloads. See [projection.rs]([REDACTED:path]), [projection.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Reviewer UI states for ready, weak matches, missing metadata, unsupported fork, GitHub unavailable, etc. See [trail_contract.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Optional lazy summary/classification/signals/chat overlays in Agent Trail, off the critical path. See [http.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n\\n**Limitations / Unknowns**\\n\\n- Association quality depends on captured GitButler environment and index hits; weak branch-only matches are explicitly modeled, not hidden.\\n- Redaction catches secrets, paths, UUIDs, entropy-looking tokens, and sensitive assignment names, but it is not a magic DLP guarantee. See [redaction.rs]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Agent Trail docs warn it does not verify claims against the PR diff; the trail is context, not proof. See [agent-trail.md]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- `agent-trail` currently pins `but-agentlog`/`git-meta-lib` by Git revision, not local path deps, so sibling repo state may differ from the exact built dependency. See [Cargo.toml]([REDACTED:path]).\\n- Private support exists in code, but docs still describe public-only v1. Treat that as an unresolved product/deployment boundary.\\n\\n**Why This Is Different From Generic Memory Tools**\\n\\nGeneric memory tools remember “what the agent/user said.” This stack preserves reviewable, Git-addressed evidence: what session touched which branch/review/change, how it relates to a PR, what got published, and what a reviewer is allowed to see.\\n\\nThe big difference is lifecycle and trust boundary. Memory tools usually optimize retrieval; this optimizes provenance, publication, redaction, sync, and review. It is closer to “agent work attached to Git history” than “agent has a long-term brain.”\\n\\nI only inspected local files and did not edit anything.\"}}\n<[REDACTED:path]>","prompt_source":"system_injected","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T11:30:57.386Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}